{
  "A chemical formula uses element symbols and subscripts to show:": "",
  "The color of the compound": "",
  "The types and numbers of atoms in a compound": "",
  "Only the charge of the compound": "",
  "Only the mass of the compound": "",
  "A chemical formula like H₂O tells us which elements are present (H and O) and how many atoms of each (2 H, 1 O) through subscripts.": "",
  "In H₂O, the subscript 2 indicates there are:": "",
  "2 oxygen atoms": "",
  "2 water molecules": "",
  "Hydrogen with charge 2": "",
  "2 hydrogen atoms": "",
  "A subscript applies to the element directly before it. In H₂O, the 2 follows H, meaning 2 hydrogen atoms per molecule of water.": "",
  "The formula for calcium chloride (Ca²⁺ and Cl⁻) is:": "",
  "CaCl": "",
  "Ca₃Cl₂": "",
  "CaCl₂": "",
  "Ca₂Cl": "",
  "Ca²⁺ needs two Cl⁻ ions to balance charges. Using the criss-cross method: Ca's 2+ becomes Cl's subscript → CaCl₂.": "",
  "When writing formulas for ionic compounds, the total charges must:": "",
  "Be all positive": "",
  "Balance to zero": "",
  "Equal the number of atoms": "",
  "Be all negative": "",
  "Ionic compounds are electrically neutral. The total positive charge from cations must equal the total negative charge from anions.": "",
  "The formula for aluminum sulfate (Al³⁺ and SO₄²⁻) is:": "",
  "AlSO₄": "",
  "Al(SO₄)₃": "",
  "Al₃(SO₄)₂": "",
  "Al₂(SO₄)₃": "",
  "Criss-cross: Al's 3 becomes the subscript for SO₄, and SO₄'s 2 becomes the subscript for Al → Al₂(SO₄)₃. Total charges: 2(+3) + 3(−2) = 0.": "",
  "Parentheses in a formula like Ca(OH)₂ mean:": "",
  "The compound is organic": "",
  "The charge is negative": "",
  "The element is rare": "",
  "The subscript outside applies to the entire polyatomic ion": "",
  "In Ca(OH)₂, the subscript 2 applies to the entire hydroxide ion (OH), giving 2 oxygen and 2 hydrogen atoms per formula unit.": "",
  "The correct formula for iron(III) oxide is:": "",
  "FeO₃": "",
  "Fe₃O₂": "",
  "Fe₂O₃": "",
  "FeO": "",
  "Iron(III) means Fe³⁺. Oxide is O²⁻. Criss-cross: Fe₂O₃. Check: 2(+3) + 3(−2) = 0. Charges balance.": "",
